VALUES
(43, 11, 52, 49, 2, 14, 22, 'gather together in one the children of God', 'Unity of God''s People', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering and unification of God''s people. John 11:52 speaks of gathering the scattered children of God, while Ephesians 2:14-22 discusses making both groups one and reconciling them into one body.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 53, 44, 5, 33, 33, NULL, 'Counsel to Kill', 'Both passages emphasize a group taking counsel to slay someone. In John 11:53, the council plots to kill Jesus, while in Acts 5:33, the council considers slaying the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 53, 44, 9, 23, 23, NULL, 'Counsel to Kill Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking counsel to kill a prominent figure. In John 11:53, the plot against Jesus is established, while Acts 9:23 reflects a similar plot against Paul.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 53, 16, 4, 16, 16, NULL, 'Collaboration Against Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of collective action in response to a perceived threat. In both passages, groups come together to confront challenges, whether plotting against Jesus or defending Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 53, 16, 13, 21, 21, NULL, 'Consequences of Defiance', 'Both passages emphasize a response to actions deemed unacceptable. In John 11:53, the decision to plot against Jesus signifies a turning point, while Nehemiah 13:21 highlights a warning against continued disobedience. This connection highlights the theme of consequences for defiance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 53, 19, 2, 2, 2, 'took counsel together for to put him to death', 'Counsel Against the Anointed', 'This connection highlights the theme of rulers conspiring against God''s anointed. Both passages emphasize the act of taking counsel together to oppose the Lord and His chosen one.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 53, 19, 31, 13, 13, 'took counsel together for to put him to death', 'Counsel Against Life', 'Both passages emphasize the plotting against a life. In John 11:53, the leaders conspire to kill Jesus, while Psalms 31:13 describes a similar situation where many devise to take away the psalmist''s life.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 53, 24, 38, 4, 4, 'put him to death', 'Plot Against the Innocent', 'Both passages emphasize a desire to put a man to death due to perceived threats to the people. In John, the leaders conspire against Jesus, while in Jeremiah, the princes seek the death of a prophet for weakening morale.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 54, 43, 7, 1, 1, 'walked no more openly among the Jews', 'Jesus'' Avoidance of Danger', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' decision to avoid public exposure due to threats against his life. In John 11:54, he no longer walked openly among the Jews, while in John 7:1, he chose not to walk in Jewry for the same reason.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 54, 14, 13, 19, 19, 'Ephraim', 'Connection through the city of Ephraim', 'Both passages mention the city of Ephraim, linking them geographically. This connection highlights the significance of Ephraim in the narratives of both Jesus and Abijah.', 'keyword', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 54, 10, 13, 23, 23, 'Ephraim', 'Connection through Location and Seclusion', 'Both passages emphasize locations near Ephraim, highlighting a theme of seclusion. In John, Jesus retreats to a city called Ephraim, while in 2 Samuel, Absalom hosts an event in Baal-hazor, which is beside Ephraim.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 54, 43, 4, 1, 3, NULL, 'Jesus'' Movement and Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' decision to leave Judea to avoid conflict with the Pharisees. In John 11:54, he withdraws to Ephraim, while in John 4:1-3, he departs to Galilee, indicating a pattern of movement in response to growing tensions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 54, 43, 10, 40, 40, NULL, 'Jesus'' Movement and Location', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' movement to remote areas. In John 11:54, he goes to Ephraim, while in John 10:40, he retreats beyond Jordan, indicating a pattern of seeking solitude.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 54, 43, 18, 20, 20, 'walked no more openly among the Jews', 'Public vs. Private Teaching', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Jesus'' withdrawal from public teaching in John 11:54 and his assertion of openly teaching in John 18:20. Both passages emphasize the nature of Jesus'' communication with the Jews, reflecting a shift from openness to a more secluded approach.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 55, 14, 30, 17, 20, 'to purify themselves', 'Purification for Passover', 'This connection highlights the theme of purification before the Passover. Both passages emphasize the necessity of being sanctified to partake in the Passover, as seen in the actions of the people in Jerusalem and the Levites in Hezekiah''s time.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 55, 58, 9, 13, 14, 'purify themselves', 'Purification and Sacrifice Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of purification in both passages. John 11:55 discusses the Jews'' need for purification before Passover, while Hebrews 9:13-14 contrasts this with the superior purification offered through the blood of Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 55, 1, 35, 2, 2, NULL, 'Purification and Cleansing Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being clean and prepared for significant events. In John, the purification before Passover reflects a similar call to cleanliness in Genesis, where Jacob instructs his household to be clean.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 55, 2, 19, 10, 10, 'to purify themselves', 'Purification Before Sacred Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of purification before significant religious observances. Both passages emphasize the necessity of sanctifying oneself, as seen in the call to ''purify themselves'' in John and ''wash their clothes'' in Exodus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 55, 43, 2, 13, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Passover References', 'Both passages emphasize the proximity of the Passover, indicating a significant time for the Jewish people. This connection highlights the importance of Jerusalem as a focal point during this festival.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 55, 43, 6, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Passover References', 'Both passages emphasize the proximity of the Passover, indicating its significance in the narrative. The mention of the Passover in both contexts highlights the importance of this feast in Jewish tradition.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 55, 2, 12, 11, 14, 'passover', 'Connection of Passover Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Passover as a time of purification and remembrance. John 11:55 mentions the preparation for Passover, while Exodus 12:11-14 describes the original Passover and its importance as a memorial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 56, 43, 7, 11, 11, 'sought they for Jesus', 'Seeking Jesus at the Feast', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking Jesus during a feast. In John 11:56, the people are questioning whether Jesus will come to the feast, while in John 7:11, they are actively looking for him at the feast.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 56, 43, 11, 7, 8, 'he will not come to the feast', 'Concern for Jesus'' Safety', 'Both passages emphasize the concern for Jesus'' safety as he contemplates returning to Judea. In John 11:56, people are questioning whether Jesus will come to the feast, while in John 11:7-8, the disciples express fear about the Jews wanting to stone him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 57, 19, 109, 4, 4, NULL, 'Adversaries and Prayer Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of adversaries in both passages. In John 11:57, the chief priests and Pharisees act as adversaries seeking to capture Jesus, while in Psalms 109:4, the speaker acknowledges adversaries despite their love, turning to prayer.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 57, 43, 5, 16, 18, 'that they might take him', 'Persecution of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility towards Jesus from the Jewish leaders. In John 5:16-18, the Jews sought to slay him for his actions, while in John 11:57, the chief priests and Pharisees actively sought to capture him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 57, 43, 8, 59, 59, NULL, 'Threats Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the hostility towards Jesus from religious leaders. In John 11:57, the chief priests and Pharisees seek to capture him, while in John 8:59, they attempt to stone him, illustrating a consistent pattern of opposition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 57, 43, 9, 22, 22, 'that they might take him', 'Fear of Jewish Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of repercussions from Jewish leaders. In John 11:57, the commandment to capture Jesus reflects the authority of the chief priests and Pharisees, while John 9:22 shows the fear of being expelled from the synagogue for acknowledging Jesus as the Christ.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 11, 57, 43, 10, 39, 39, 'that they might take him', 'Attempts to Capture Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the ongoing efforts of the chief priests and Pharisees to capture Jesus. In John 11:57, they command anyone who knows Jesus'' whereabouts to reveal it, while John 10:39 shows their previous attempts to take him, highlighting a continuous theme of opposition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
